\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 Each running process has a button on the bar and you can click on a button to switch to that task.  If you right click instead, a popup menu lets you minimize, maximize or close the window.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21\qc \{bmc taskbar.bmp\}
\par \pard \s21 
\par The start button has a special popup menu that lets you setup the Taskbar.  Choose {\uldb Taskbar Properties}{\v TaskbarProp} from this menu 
to adjust the settings.  You can configure the Taskbar to always stay on screen or hide when the cursor moves off it.  It will always pop up when the cursor reaches the bottom of the screen.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Drag and drop
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
If a program normally accepts files dropped into itsicon from File Manager, you can drop files from Calmira into that program's taskbar button.  You can also copy and move files and folders by dropping them into the taskbar buttons for icon windows.  A hi
dden taskbar will pop up when you drag objects to the base of the screen .
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 The Applet Tray
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
This is located on the Taskbar's clock, and it can hold a few icons for commonly used utilities.  These programs are treated slightly differently from those launched by normal shortcuts.  Firstly, Calmira doesn't runa new copy of the program if it is alre
ady running.  Secondly, the applets are not shown on the Taskbar, since they can be brought forward from the Applet Tray.  You can add and remove applets from the Taskbar Properties dialog.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Using aliases in the Applet Tray
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
If you need applet tray icons with more detailed settings (e.g. a specific icon), create a new subdirectory called "Tray" in Calmira's home directory and create some aliases there.  Open the Taskbar Properties dialog, and close it again to force the Apple
t Tray to reload.  The aliases will appear as small icons.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 You cannot directly edit the icons that are in the tray -- you need to edit the original aliases and then reload them.  They behave like normal aliases, so each click will start a fresh instance of the program.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Excluding programs
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
There are some programs which you may not wish to appear Taskbar.  For example, programs which have icons that change appearance, like the Windows Clock, should stay as an icon on the desktop. Also, space on the Taskbar is valuable, so you should not show
 a Taskbar button for programs you don't often switch to.  Use the Exclusion tab page in the Taskbar Properties dialog to specify which programs to exclude.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Moving and resizing the taskbar
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 If you drag the taskbar's
 body panel, you can move it to the top or bottom of the screen.  If you move the cursor to the inner edge of the taskbar, it changes to a double headed arrow.  This lets you resize the bar to show multiple rows of buttons.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Showing the system menu over buttons
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
When you right click on a taskbar button, Calmira normally shows a popup menu with four standard commands.  If your programs have extra commands on their system menus, you can use the Taskbar Properties dialog to make the real system menu appear when
 youright click.
\par \pard \s21 
