\pard\plain \s16 \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 +} 00000}} Shortcuts and Aliases
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par Shortcuts and aliases are {\i references} -- they point to another object such as a disk drive, folder, or file.  When you open or drop things into a reference, the effect is the same as if you had ope
ned or dropped into the original object.  You can also create a link to an {\uldb Internet}{\v Internet} address.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Shortcuts
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 These are icons on the desktop, and you can create them in two ways: either drag an icon out of a window and release the mouse, or right click on the {\uldb desktop}{\v Desktop}
 and choose an item from the New Shortcut submenu.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21\qc \{bmc shortcut.bmp\}
\par \pard \s21 
\par The shortcut is saved in Calmira's INI file when you quit.  To edit its properties, click on its caption and choose {\uldb Properties}{\v ReferenceProp} from the menu.  Shortcut
s are effective when used sparingly -- you would probably have shortcuts of your disk drives and a few important folders and utilities on your desktop.  Each shortcut is a real window and uses the same amount of resources.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
Since shortcuts are ordinary desktop icons, some programs like the Windows task manager may re-arrange them to the bottom of the screen.  If this happens, you can use the Restore Shortcuts command from the desktop menu to move the back to their previous l
ocations.  Calmira has a replacement task manager that does not have such a problem (see {\uldb Installation}{\v Installing} for details).
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Aliases
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
These are small files (with an extension ALS) containing an icon and some data that points to the original object. To create aliases of visible objects, drag them to another folder or window, and hold down the Shift key before releasing the mouse.  To cre
ate an alias of something not currently visible, right click between the icons and choose Create Alias from the window menu.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21\qc \{bmc alias.bmp\}
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 Aliases are just like other files, and you can copy, move or delete them without affecting the original object.  To change their properties, right click and select the Edit Alias command.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
You can use aliases to give the effect of a free floating program group: move aliases into the one folder, create a shortcut of thefolder, and change its icon.  They are also useful for creating "virtual links" to other folders, to change the apparent str
ucture of your directory tree.
\par \pard \s21 
