\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 If you right click on your wallpaper, the desktop menu appears, which gives you fast access to frequently used features.  There are facilities to let you create a shortcut at the point where you clicked, and arrange desktop icons and windows.

\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Exposing hidden shortcuts
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
When the desktop is hidden behind other windows, you can bring your shortcut icons forward by right clicking on the desktop while holding down the left mouse button.  If the desktop is covered by a maximized window, you use the same method on the Taskbar'
s main body panel, or just double click on the Taskbar.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Opening and creating folders
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
The Open Folder command is particularly useful because it lets you quickly get to any directory without travelling through the tree.  To see only certain files, add a wildcard (which must include ? or *) after the folder name.  For example c:\\Windows\\
System\\*.dll.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 To create a new folder, select this menu command, type in a new folder name, and you will be asked whether it should be created.  The new folder is opened for you in a blank window.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Differences between Open Folder and Run dialog
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 You can open an icon window from the {\uldb Run Program dialog}{\v RunProgram}
 by typing in a folder name, which gives you the benefit of a history list.  However, the Open Folder command is a little more powerful because it can create new folders, and you don't needto type in the full pathname -- if you omit a drive, Calmira uses 
the drive on which Windows is installed; if you omit a leading backslash, Calmira adds it for you.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 Some examples of what you can type for Open Folder:
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard {\f5 Fully qualified folder name:\tab }{\f11\fs18 c:\\programs --> c:\\programs}{\f5 
\par Leading backslash:\tab \tab }{\f11\fs18 \\programs   --> c:\\programs}{\f5 
\par No leading punctuation:\tab \tab }{\f11\fs18 programs    --> c:\\programs}{\f5 
\par Drive identifier:\tab \tab \tab }{\f11\fs18 a:          --> a:\\}{\f5 
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
When Calmira needs to fill in the full path, it uses the drive on which Windows is installed.  Thisis because the "current directory" has little meaning since Calmira operates across all drives.  This is different from the Open batch file -- if you type "
Open programs" at the DOS prompt, Calmira assumes that you want to open the "programs" directory in the current directory (which now has a meaning).
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Creating a new folder on the desktop
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Use the desktop menu to create a folder shortcut.  In the {\uldb Shortcut Properties dialog}{\v ReferenceProp}
, enter a caption and the name of a new directory, then press OK.  Calmira will ask you whether you wish to create a new directory.
