\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Opening URLs through DDE
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Calmira can be set up to use your internet browser when opening URL\rquote s.  By default, Calmira is set up asuming Netscape 3.0 is installed in C:\\
NETSCAPE. To specify another browser, you have to set up its directory by following these steps:
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s22\keep \f5\fs20\lang2057 1. Open the {\uldb System Properties dialog}{\v SystemProp}.
\par \pard \s22\keep 2. Select the Advanced tab page.
\par 3. Open the [Internet] section.
\par 4. Modify the ServiceApplication string to point to your browser.
\par \pard \s22\keep     {\i Do} include the full pathname.
\par     {\i Do not} include the .EXE file extension.
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 For example, to open Internet Explorer:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 [Internet]
\par \pard \s20 ServiceApplication=c:\\iexplore\\iexplore
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 To open Netscape 4.0:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 [Internet]
\par \pard \s20 ServiceApplication=c:\\netscape\\program\\navstart
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Opening URLs using a command line
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Some browsers may not work correctly using DDE, especially if they take a long time to load, causing a DDE timeout.  In these cases, Calmira can open an Internet shortcut by running a specific p
rogram.  If the CommandLine string in the [Internet] section is present, it will override any DDE settings.  Use the %url% variable to insert the address.
\par 
\par \pard \s21 To open URLs using Navigator 4.0, you can add:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 [Internet]
\par \pard \s20 CommandLine=c:\\netscape\\program\\navstart.exe -browser %url%
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 For Internet Explorer 3.0, you can try:
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 
\par \pard \s20 [Internet]
\par CommandLine=c:\\iexplore\\iexplore.exe %url%
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Specifying URL prefixes
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 In the [Internet] section, the URLPrefixes setting determines the strings that Calmira uses to identify an Internet 
address.  When it processes a command line, Calmira looks for the prefixes at the beginning of the command, and calls your web browser if one is found.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 You can modify this setting to include any additional prefixes such as "www." or "ftp.".  Most web browsers now allow you to omit the protocol indicator.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b\cf2 Note:} Adding these prefixes will cause your browser to execute when you open a file who\rquote s name begins with \ldblquote www.\rdblquote  or \ldblquote ftp.\rdblquote  (ie. \ldblquote www.txt\rdblquote ).
\par \pard \s21 {\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Shortcuts and aliases
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Use these to quickly mark a web page or other Internet address.  When you create a new {\uldb shortcut or alias}{\v References} and choose {\i Internet}
 as the type, Calmira looks for your browser program.  If the browser is running, the current location's title and URL are captured for you.  Otherwise, you must enter the details yourself.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Run dialog
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 You can type a URL into the {\uldb Run Program dialog}{\v RunProgram} to open it.  Your browser is launched if it is not already running.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Start Menu
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Type in a URL into the {\i Command line} field, and the effect is the same as for th
e Run Dialog.  You can use the Start Menu to organise Navigator style bookmarks missing from the Internet Explorer 3.0 Favourites feature.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 To avoid having to keep the {\uldb Start Menu Properties dialog}{\v StartMenuProp}
 open while you are browsing (or paste URLs manually), create aliases of URLs in a temporary folder.  Afterwards, the aliases can be dropped into the dialog's menu tree, which automatically converts the captions and addresses.
\par \pard \s21 
