\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 Open this dialog by right clicking on the Start button of the {\uldb Taskbar}, and choose Start Properties.  This dialog is not modal, so you can switch windows and drop items into the tree.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Creating new items
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 There are three ways of doing this:
\par \pard \s21 
\par 1.  Press the Add or Insert buttons on the toolbar.
\par 2.  Drag and drop files and folders from icon windows straight into the tree.
\par 3.  Press the Import Groups button to copy items from Program Manager.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Creating new sub-menus
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 A sub-menu starts off as a normal menu item.  When you use the Insert button or drag nodes onto it, it becomes a menu.  When the contents are deleted, it becomes an item again.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Copying and moving items and sub-menus
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Simply drag a node's caption to move it.  To drop a node into a closed sub-menu, hold down ALT before releasing the mouse button.  To copy a single item, hold down the CTRL key when dropping.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Editing an item
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 To edit a menu item, you can double click on a node with no descendants to display the {\uldb Menu Item Properties dialog}{\v MenuItemProp}
.  Otherwise, click on the Edit button, press Enter, or right click for the popup menu.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Adding items through the Computer
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 You can drag and drop objects onto the {\uldb Computer}{\v Computer} icon, and they will appear in the Start Menu Properties dialog the next time you open it.  This saves you from having to keep the d
ialog on screen for long periods.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Rebuilding the Start Menu
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
If you are displaying a Windows 95 style menu with icons, the icons need to be gathered up before the Start Menu can be displayed again.  The "rebuild in background" checkbox lets you carry on with other tasks while this occurs -- the cursor changes to a 
pointer with an hourglass attached, and returns to normal when the Start Menu is ready for use.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 Note: if you have modified icon or bitmap files used for the menu, you must check the Rebuild check
box so that it shows a checkmark. This forces a full rebuild. By default, Calmira performs a fast rebuild, only changing icons that have beed added or changed during editing. Calmira shows a grayed checkbox in this case.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Adding items from installation programs
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
If Calmira is running as the shell, it can detect input from installation programs, and create new Start Menu items instead of Program Manager icons.  When an installation program has finished running, open the Start Menu Properties dialog, and the n
ew groups and items will appear in the tree.  Press OK to accept the new entries, or Cancel to discard them.
\par \pard \s21 
