\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Built-in menu commands
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Instead of specifying a program to run, the {\i command line} field of a menu item can open or activate a window in Calmira.  The recognised commands are in the drop-down list.  The $Folder command opens an {\uldb 
icon window}{\v IconWindows}, and requires a directory name as parameter.  If wildcard characters * or ? are present in the parameter, they are used as the filter.  For example:
\par \pard \s21 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx3012\cellx7332 \pard \s21\intbl {\f11\fs18 $Folder c:\\windows\\*.exe}{\f11 \cell }\pard \s21\intbl displays all the executables\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f6\fs20\lang2057 \row \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx3012
\cellx7332 \pard\plain \s21\intbl \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\f11\fs18 $Folder c:\\windows}{\f11 \cell }\pard \s21\intbl displays all files\cell \pard\plain \intbl \f6\fs20\lang2057 \row \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 The icon property
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 To use a Windows bitmap (bmp) file for a menu item instead of an icon, type in the full name of the bitmap file in the {\i Icon from} edit box. This bitmap should be 16 x 16 pixels, but can have any number of colours.

\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 To show a menu item without any icon (which also saves memory), specify <none> in the icon field.  If you just leave it blank, Calmira picks the icon for you.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Adding menu separators
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 A dash "-" as the first character of a caption will turn the entry into a separator line.  Each item must have a different caption, so use something like -1, -2 ... for multiple separators.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Breaking menus into columns
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 You can break a large menu into {\i equal sized} columns.  Edit the {\b parent menu} item's caption, and insert *<number> at the front of the string.  For example to 
break the Games menu into three equal columns, change the caption to *3Games.  The *3 will not be shown in the actual menu, but you need to include it when assigning a {\uldb hot-key}{\v KeyboardShortcuts}.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
If you want to break up a menu into columns which are not equal, you can create dummy menu items to fill out the space. The trick is to make use of the "*n" column dividers within the columns themselves!  This allows you to create unique items with blank 
captions -- you can use "*1", "*2"..."*9" and Calmira will chop off the asterisks and digits.  Finally, set the icon to <none>.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Using the keyboard with the Start Menu
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
An ampersand "&" in front of any letter in the caption will underline it for use as the accelerator.  To enable the keyboard for use with the Start Menu, Calmira must grab the focus whenever the menu appears.  Turn this feature on in the Preferences page.
  You can also specify a {\uldb keyboard shortcut}{\v KeyboardShortcuts} ("hot-key") to bring up the Start Menu.
\par \pard \s21 
