\cs15\f6\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 +} 00000}} Taskbar Properties dialog
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 Open this dialog by right clicking on the Start button and choosing Taskbar Properties.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Refresh interval setting
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 This determines how often the Taskbar updates the button captions and removes any buttons for windows that have disappeared from the screen without being detected in the normal way.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Adding items to the Applet Tray
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 When you press the Add button, you are prompted for a new entry.  Enter the popup hint to be displayed, an equals sign, and the program's full pathname.  For example:
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 Calculator=c:\\windows\\calc.exe
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 You can only add Windows programs to the applet tray, and these programs should only use one main window, otherwise they may not be restored or re-activated correctly.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 See the {\uldb Taskbar}{\v Taskbar} topic for information about using aliases in the applet tray.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Adding exclusions
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 To exclude an ordinary program such as the Windows clock, just add its full pathname to the list.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 If a program shows more than one window, the optional window class name lets you exclude only certain types of windows.  You can find class names by selecting {\i Spy}
 from the Start button's menu, and watching the button hints, which will now tell you the filename and class of each task.  When you have found the class name, separate it from the filename with a single space.
\par \pard \s21 
