\pard\plain \s16 \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 +} 00000}} Defining keyboard shortcuts
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 
Calmira lets you assign hot-keys to activate any window, menu item or desktop shortcut.  Since many programs define their own keyboard commands, Calmira only allows you to specify key combinations that include two or more out of Ctrl, Alt and Shift.

\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard {\f5 Fill the [Keyboard] section of the INI file with keyboard mappings in the format caption=key.  For example,
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 [Keyboard]
\par \pard \s20 System=Shift+Ctrl+F1
\par Drive (C:)=Ctrl+Alt+C
\par c:\\windows=Ctrl+Alt+W
\par Notepad=Alt+Shift+N
\par \pard\plain \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 
\par When you press keys together with Ctrl, Alt and Shift, Calmira searches the list and obtains the caption.  It then searches all Calmira windows, }{\f5\uldb shortcuts}{\v\f5 References}{\f5 , and the }{\f5\uldb Start Menu}{\v\f5 StartMenu}{\f5 
 for a match (in that order), and activates the object if a matching caption is found.  If you specify a folder which is not shown in a window, then the folder is opened for you.
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard {\f5 Finally, if nothing matches the text, the search extends to all windows on the screen, even those belonging to other applications.
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 In the above example, Ctrl+
Shift+F1 will restore the computer window.  Ctrl+Alt+C might activate a shortcut to drive C.  Ctrl+Alt+W will open the windows folder, and Shiftl+Alt+N could run Notepad if it's in the Start Menu.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b\cf2 Note:} to enable keyboard shortcuts to work from inside {\i any} Windows program, you must turn this feature on from the {\uldb System Properties Dialog}{\v SystemProp}.
\par \pard \s21 
