}} {\cs15\f6\fs16\up6 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s16 \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\cs15\fs16\up6 +} 00000}} Environment strings
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par {\uldb Shortcuts and aliases}{\v References} and {\uldb Start Menu}{\v StartMenu} items can use MS-DOS environment variables in their settings.  The {\i Target}, {\i Parameters}, {\i Command}, {\i Icon file} and {\i Working Folder}
 fields (where applicable) can contain environment variable names (surrounded by %) like lines in MS-DOS batch files.  When you activate an object, the variable values are substituted for the names.
\par \pard \s21 
\par 
\par \pard \s21 {\b\cf9 Special environment strings
\par }{\b 
\par }\pard \s21 {\b %currentfolder%} points to the directory showing in the active {\uldb icon window}{\v IconWindows} (if none are active, the variable is empty).  This is particularly useful for the {\i Working Folder}
 field when you want to create or modify
 files in the folder being displayed.  For instance, if you use it for a Notepad shortcut, Notepad will always start up in the directory you are viewing, so you can open and save/create files without having to huntthrough the tree.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %currentdrive%}
 contains the drive letter of the active icon window, and can be used in a similar way to %currentfolder%.  Additionally, it is alsoavailable while the Disk Properties dialog is open, so your disk utility can be targeted a specific drive.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %droppedfiles%} is only valid immediately after files have been dropped into a file shortcut or alias.  It contains the list of filenames, and you can place it in the {\i Parameters}
 field to insert the filenames between other parameters.  If %droppedfiles% is omitted, the files are just appended to the parameters list.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %filename%} is only valid when used with the Inspect program and default viewer (set from the {\uldb File System Properties}{\v FileSystemProp} dialog), and with entries in the [File Viewers] section.  It contains the name of the focu
sed file, and is used to specify where on the command line to insert the filename.  If you omit this variable, the filename is appended to the end of the command line.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %calmira%} points to the program's home directory.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %comspec%} is defined automatically by MS-DOS, and gives the filename of the command interpreter (i.e. the MS-DOS shell), which is usually command.com.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b %windir%} is defined automatically by Windows and points to the Windows directory.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b Note}: a pre-defined environment variable that specifies a directory will not contain a final backslash unless it is the root directory.  For example %windir% usually has the value "c:\\windows" with no trailing backslash.
\par \pard \s21 
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 User defined variables
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 The [Environment] section of the INI file is added to Calmira's own environment after loading, so it has the same effect as the MS-DOS {\i set}
 command.  As with MS-DOS, don't add the % characters when making settings -- they are only used when variables are referred to.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 Use this section to store your own identifiers, such a
s folder locations and device names.  When a folder or device changes, just edit the environment and all shortcuts, aliases and menu items will refer to the right place automatically.  Settings made in the [Environment] section only affect Calmira, and do
es not require extra environment memory to be allocated.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b Example
\par }\pard \s21 Suppose your CD-ROM drive is F: but it might change in the near future.  You can add the line cdrom=f: to the environment, and make your shortcuts and Start Menu items point to %cdrom%\\filena
me.exe.  When you change the value of %cdrom%, all your links are instantly updated.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b\cf2 Note:} the icon {\i index} is not affected by the environment, so you should use something like %filename%(1) when re-mapping the icon file.
