\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 Calmira can read and execute commands from text files, allowing you to carry out multipleoperations in one g
o, like very simple batch files.  Because the same file can be accessed from both Windows and an MS-DOS box running in Enhanced Mode, scripts also allow you to run Windows programs from the DOS prompt like Windows 95 and NT.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 For example, you could type "start notepad" in an MS-DOS box to open the Windows Notepad.  Or you can create a shortcut that runs three programs instead of just one.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 This article describes how to use script files with Calmira.  To learn how to write the scripts, see the topic {\uldb Format of a script file}{\v ScriptFormat}.
\par \pard \s21 
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 Getting started
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par 1.  Open the {\uldb System Properties}{\v SystemProp} dialog.
\par \pard \s21 2.  Enable both MS-DOS and Windows scripts check boxes.
\par 3.  Open your Autoexec.bat in Notepad.
\par \pard \s21 4.  Add the command {\f11 set }{\f11\fs18 TEMPSCRIPT=c:\\temp\\calmira.tmp}
\par \pard \s21 5.  Reboot the computer.
\par 6.  Try out the Start batch file from a DOS window.
\par 7.  Using a text editor, create the following script named test.run:
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057    start
\par \pard \s20    c:\\windows
\par    notepad
\par    start
\par    c:\\windows
\par    write
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 8.  Double click on the icon of test.run -- two programs load at once.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Running scripts from Windows
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
The [Scripts] section has a WinScriptExtension setting that determines the files which Calmira will attempt to read when you double click on them in an icon window.  The default value is ".run", so all files with an extension of .run are assumed to be tex
t scripts.  The System Properties dialog has a checkbox to run this feature on and off.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Running scripts from MS-DOS
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Calmira checks for the presence of a special script file every second.  By default, it looks for the file c:\\temp\\calmira.run.  This filename can be changed using the DosScriptFilename setting in the [Scripts] section.

\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 If the file exists, Calmira loads it into memory, deletes it immediately, and then processes the lines one by one, just as if you had double clicked on the file from an icon window.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Generating scripts from MS-DOS
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Ordinary MS-DOS batch files can easily be used to create the scripts from the commands that you type (which is why each parameter is stored on a separate line!).  A bat
ch file simply echoes a combination of keywords and its own parameters, and redirects them to be appended to the script file.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
There is a slight problem -- since MS-DOS programs are pre-emptively multi-tasked under Enhanced Mode Windows 3.1, Calmira could try and read the script before thebatch file has finished generating the lines.  So instead of writing the script directly, ba
tch files should send the lines to another file, and then rename that file to the required script at the very end.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Sample batch file
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 The supplied batch file, {\i start.bat}
 expect an MS-DOS environment variable called TempScript, which points to a temporary filename in the same directory as the target script file (so that a simple rename will make the script "appear" for Calmira).  You can set TempScript to c:\\temp\\
calmira.tmp in your Autoexec.bat if the default c:\\temp\\calmira.run is looked for.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 Study the batch file to see how it work.  It resembles an MS-DOS command, complete with error handling and help.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 START batch command
\par \pard\plain \f6\fs20\lang2057 {\f5 Starting with Calmira II 3.2, the newer }{\i\f5 start.bat}{\f5  replaces all older Open, Start, Explore and Folder commands.  It requires the supplied }{\i\f5 direxist.exe}{\f5 
 utility to detect the existence of a directory.
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard {\f5 To use start.bat, copy the file and direxist.exe into a directory on the MS-DOS path.  Type }{\f11\fs18 start /?}{\f5  for details.  You can use it to open folders, programs or documents, and it will try to determine a sensible choice.
\par }\pard {\f5 
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Direxist.exe returns an errorlevel of 1 if the directory parameter exists.  All root directories are onsidered to exist, even if the drive is invalid.  The Turbo Pascal source code is included.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 {\b\cf2 Note:} Only one script can be executing at any one time.  Scripts cannot run themselves, or other scripts.
\par \pard \s21 
