\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 {\*\bkmkstart Optimising}{\*\bkmkend Optimising}
\par \pard \s21 Many of these issues are inter-related, so more conservative settings are likely to use less memory and resources, {\i and} speed up your system.  Experiment to find the most effective setup for your PC.
\par \pard \s21 
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 Using less resources
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 Resources are mainly consumed by windows (which include shortcuts, buttons, list boxes 
etc.), menu items, and graphics objects such as bitmaps.  It is difficult to avoid using a lot of resources if you want an advanced graphical front-end, but if you areshort of resources, you can use slightly less by changing the way you run Calmira.

\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Use shortcuts sparingly -- each one requires one window for the icon and another one for the caption.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Make use of the multi-window closing facilities (keyboard commands and the desktop menu) to close unwanted icon windows as
 soon as you have finished using them.  As well as window handles, each icon window owns a set of popup menus too.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Close modeless dialog boxes (Find, Run etc.) as soon as possible.
\par 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Don't put too many items in the Start Menu, because each menu item uses up resources, and it's easy to forget how large the menu has become.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 Using less memory
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 If you only have 4MB RAM, then you should also read the topic on optimising Windows to make sure that memory is not being wasted.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Use aliases sparingly -- each alias can use over 3K when it is being displayed in a window.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Make use of the window closing facilities to close unnecessary icon windows, especially those containing many aliases.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab 
Calmira's memory heap may become fragmented after long periods of use, and some memory will not be released even when you close icon windows.  The best way to prevent this problem is to limit the number of icon windows that are ever open at the 
same time, if they contain a large number of files.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Don't specify too many document icons in the [Icons] section, because once loaded (when Calmira needs to display it), a document icon is not unloaded until Calmira finishes.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Reduce the file types which are searched for icons.  This is useful if you have directories full of files containing icons, ICO files in particular.  Just searching EXE files is usually enough.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\} \tab Don't put too many items in the Start Menu, because each menu item uses a few hundred bytes of memory, and each small icon requires a 16x16 bitmap, which also consumes memory.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 Speeding up Calmira
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Reduce the file types which are searched for icons to just EXE files.  DLL files rarely contain useful information in their icons.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Turn off 4DOS description support if you never use it.
\par 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Limit the number of icons used for document files to prevent Calmira from extracting too many icons.  You can
 override the registry settings by using the [Icons] section to map different file extensions to the same icon, which loads it only once.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Turn off the miniature icon view to make scrolling faster -- shrinking icons is a very slow process.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Turn off the solid highlight bar on the Start Menu to significantly increase drawing speed.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Turn off the option scroll views while scroll bars are dragged (in the System Properties dialog).
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab When searching for files, only specify one wildcard and clear the list between searches.  This lets Calmira bypass the checks for duplicate entries and is much faster for long lists.
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 
\par \pard \s21\fi-270\li270\tx270 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Don't keep too much trash because the bin checks through the files when Calmira loads, to read the size and date attributes.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 {\cf9 Streamlining the INI file
\par }\pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 There are two sections in Calmira.ini which should be well maintained to avoid slowing down the program.  You should quit Calmira and edit the INI file with a text editor for this.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
If your icon windows have their positions saved then you need to clear out the [Window Positions] section to prevent it becoming too big.  Calmira doesn't update this section when folders have been moved or deleted, and it can grow very quickly.  Also, ma
ke sure that the [Window Captions] section does not contain unnecessary entries.
\par \pard \s21 
