\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 No stack checking!
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Stack checking has been turned off to marginally increase performance, and the stack size increased to 20KB for the main program and decreased to 8K
B for the Taskbar.  Calmira actually needs a sizeable stack to handle recursion simultaneously with background "threads" such as file copying and re-building of the Start Menu.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 
While it is not totally safe to remove the stack checking code, the risk of overflowing the stack is small.  All recursive procedures and functions used in the main program have activation records much less than 256 bytes, and they are mostly involved wit
h travelling the directory tree, which must be limited to 79 character pathnames anyway.  Even with four simultaneous threads at their deepest point of recursion, there should be more than enough stack for the VCL and other transient function calls.

\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Use of undocumented functions
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
Calmira uses two features of Windows that are not documented in the API help file, although they are generally known.  The first is the drag-drop server implementation in DropServ.pas, which builds the memory object that accompanies the WMDropFiles messag
e.  The second is the WMSysCommand parameter codes used in ExtForm.pas for window resizing.  File System Change Notification, as described by Schulman et al, has not been used in this release.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Exported interface
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Calmira does not have an API, DDE or otherwise, for communication with other programs.  See the CalMsgs.pas unit for details of internal messages that could be utilised.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 There are two reserved and currently unused commands for the WMCalmira registered message, one of which is CM_RELOADOPTIONS.  This message causes as many settings as possible to be re
loaded from the INI file, and might be used by a future configuration utility.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 The other one is CM_STARTPROP.  This message may be use by setup programs, for either Calmira itself, or other applications, to display the Start Menu Properties dialog and force DDE message to be processed.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Tip of the Day file format
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 Tips are stored in a plain text file, which has a number on the first line indicating the number of entries in the file.  Blank lines are ignored, and lines beginning with semi-colons are consider
ed comments.  All other lines contain tips, and should be less than 255 characters in length.
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard \s21 To count the number of tips in a modified tips file, use the CountTip utility supplied in one of the source archives as both a DOS executable and the Turbo Pascal code.  Run it using:
\par \pard \s21 
\par \pard\plain \s20 \f11\fs18\cf1\lang2057 counttip < tips.txt
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 
\par \pard \s21 This will check each tip for the length limitation, as well as output the number of tips found.
\par 
\par \pard\plain \s19\sa30 \b\f5\fs20\cf1\lang2057 Possible causes of incompatibility
\par \pard\plain \s21 \f5\fs20\lang2057 The only "unusual" code that Calmira contains resides in the DLL file, which im
plements hooks for the mouse, shell, window procedures and keyboard. Their potential impact on stability has not been investigated. The desktop window is subclassed to capture right clicks, but only for convenience -- it is also possible to move the code 
into the mouse hook to avoid the problems caused by multiple utilities subclassing the desktop.
\par \pard \s21 
